BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 167.76 740 Td (Chapter 3: Holding the Hook and Yarn) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (There are two common ways to hold a crochet hook: pencil grip and knife grip.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Pencil grip holds the hook like you hold a pencil, with fingers near the middle.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Knife grip holds the hook overhand like holding a dinner knife while cutting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Neither way is wrong. Try both and use whichever feels more comfortable to you.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Hold the hook in your dominant hand. Your other hand controls the yarn tension.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Yarn tension means how tightly you hold the yarn as it feeds through your fingers.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Wrap the yarn over your index finger on your non-dominant hand.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Let it flow between your middle and ring fingers for gentle tension control.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Too tight tension makes stitches difficult to work into on the next row.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Too loose tension creates floppy, uneven fabric without good structure.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Practice holding both hook and yarn before making any stitches at all.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Consistent tension comes with practice. Do not worry if it feels awkward initially.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (3) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
18 0 obj
<< /Type /Page /Parent 2 0 R /MediaBox [0 0 612 792] /Contents 19 0 R /Resources << /Font << /F1 3 0 R /F2 4 0 R /F3 5 0 R /F4 6 0 R /F5 7 0 R >> >> >>
