BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 194.64 740 Td (Chapter 4: Making a Slip Knot) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Every crochet project begins with a slip knot on your hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Make a loop with your yarn, leaving a six-inch tail hanging down.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Reach through the loop and pull the working yarn \(the long end\) partially through.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (This creates an adjustable loop that tightens when you pull the tail.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Slide this loop onto your crochet hook and tighten gently by pulling the tail.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (The knot should slide freely on the hook without being too tight or loose.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (The loop on your hook should be snug but able to slide back and forth easily.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (If the knot is too tight, start over. You will make many slip knots in your life.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (The slip knot does not count as a stitch in your pattern.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Practice making slip knots until you can do it quickly and consistently.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (This simple knot is the starting point for every single crochet project.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Once your slip knot is on the hook, you are ready to make your first chain.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (4) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
