BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 217.68 740 Td (Chapter 5: Chain Stitch) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (The chain stitch is the foundation of almost every crochet project.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (With your slip knot on the hook, wrap the yarn over the hook from back to front.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (This motion is called a yarn over and you will do it constantly in crochet.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Pull the yarn over through the loop already on your hook. That is one chain.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Repeat: yarn over, pull through. Each time creates one more chain stitch.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Your chain should look like a series of connected V shapes on the front.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Practice making chains until they are even and consistent in size.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Count your chains by counting each V shape, not including the loop on the hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (If your chains are too tight, use a hook one size larger for the chain only.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Try to keep even tension. Chains should not be so tight they pucker.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Make a chain of twenty stitches and check that they all look similar.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (The chain is your first real stitch. Master this before moving to the next chapter.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (5) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
