BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 190.8 740 Td (Chapter 8: Half Double Crochet) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Half double crochet is between single and double crochet in height.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (It creates a lovely textured fabric that is slightly stretchy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Yarn over, insert your hook into the third chain from the hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Yarn over and pull through the chain. You have three loops on your hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Yarn over and pull through all three loops at once. That is the key difference.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (For double crochet you pull through two at a time. Here you pull through all three.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (At the end of a row, chain two and turn. The chain-two counts as a stitch.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Half double crochet creates a fabric thicker than double but less dense than single.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (It is a popular stitch for hats, baby blankets, and cozy scarves.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (The slightly different texture adds visual interest compared to other basic stitches.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Practice a swatch of twenty stitches and ten rows to get comfortable.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (You now know the three most important crochet stitches used in most patterns.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (8) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
