BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 167.76 740 Td (Chapter 9: Increasing and Decreasing) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Increasing means adding stitches to make your fabric wider or to shape projects.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (To increase, simply make two stitches in the same stitch instead of one.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (This is used when making hats, amigurumi, and any shaped project.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Decreasing means removing stitches to make your fabric narrower.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (For a single crochet decrease: insert hook in next stitch, yarn over and pull up.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Insert hook in the following stitch, yarn over and pull up. Three loops on hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Yarn over and pull through all three loops. Two stitches become one.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Invisible decrease works the same but inserts under front loops only for neatness.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Patterns tell you exactly where to increase and decrease with abbreviations.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Increases and decreases are how flat circles, spheres, and shaped items are made.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (A flat circle starts with a ring and increases evenly each round.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Practice making a flat circle to test your increasing skills before larger projects.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (9) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
