BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 198.48000000000002 740 Td (Chapter 10: Reading Patterns) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Crochet patterns use standard abbreviations that are the same worldwide.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (CH means chain, SC means single crochet, DC means double crochet.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (HDC means half double crochet, SL ST means slip stitch, SK means skip.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (INC means increase \(two stitches in one\), DEC means decrease.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Numbers in parentheses at the end of a row show total stitch count.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Asterisks mark sections that repeat: *SC 2, INC* means repeat that sequence.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Patterns specify hook size, yarn weight, and finished dimensions.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Gauge is how many stitches per inch your work measures with specific yarn and hook.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Always check gauge before starting a project where size matters like garments.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Patterns are written either in rows \(flat pieces\) or rounds \(circular items\).) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Read the entire pattern once before starting to understand the overall structure.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Start with patterns rated beginner or easy until you build confidence.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 301.2 40 Td (10) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
32 0 obj
<< /Type /Page /Parent 2 0 R /MediaBox [0 0 612 792] /Contents 33 0 R /Resources << /Font << /F1 3 0 R /F2 4 0 R /F3 5 0 R /F4 6 0 R /F5 7 0 R >> >> >>
endobj
