BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 140.88 740 Td (Chapter 14: Troubleshooting Common Mistakes) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Edges are uneven: you are likely missing the first or last stitch of each row.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Place a stitch marker in the first stitch of each row until the habit forms.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Fabric is getting wider: you are accidentally adding extra stitches somewhere.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Count stitches at the end of every row until counting becomes automatic.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Fabric is curling: this is normal for single crochet. Blocking usually fixes it.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Stitches are too tight: relax your grip and let the yarn flow more freely.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Stitches are too loose: hold yarn slightly tighter between your tension fingers.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Yarn is splitting: your hook is piercing the yarn. Insert into the whole stitch.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Lost your place: use a stitch marker on the current stitch before setting down work.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Holes in your fabric: you are skipping stitches. Insert hook under both loops.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Most beginner mistakes are solved by counting stitches and maintaining tension.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Every crocheter made these same mistakes. They are a normal part of learning.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 301.2 40 Td (14) Tj ET

endstream
